{
  "body": "Abstract breakdown of {{subject}} into floating {{geometry_set}}, limited strictly to two colors: {{color_1}} and {{color_2}}.\n\n— Concept —\nDeconstruct the recognizable form of {{subject}} into its essential geometric primitives. The viewer should be able to *almost* recognize the original subject through the arrangement, but each piece is now a clean abstracted shape — a study in pure form, color, and balance. Think Bauhaus design exercise meets contemporary 3D minimal poster.\n\n— Geometry —\nUse only the shape family: {{geometry_set}}. Each shape is rendered as a pristine, perfectly clean primitive — no surface noise, no decorative pattern, no texture overlay. Sizes vary across the composition to create rhythm and hierarchy.\n\n— Color system (STRICT — only two colors allowed) —\nEntire image limited to exactly TWO colors:\n  • Primary: {{color_1}} (dominant, used on the largest/most prominent shapes)\n  • Secondary: {{color_2}} (accent, used on supporting shapes for contrast)\nNo gradients between colors. No third color. No rainbow. No neon glow. Background color counts separately.\n\n— Composition —\n{{composition_style}}. Negative space is intentionally emphasized — at least 40–50% of the frame remains empty / breathing. Each shape has its own clear position relationship with the others. The arrangement feels considered and intentional, never random.\n\n— Depth & material —\n{{depth_style}}. Lighting is soft and even, casting only delicate shadows that anchor the shapes to the ground plane (or no shadows at all if 2D vector style is chosen).\n\n— Background —\n{{background}}. Completely free of clutter — no horizon, no patterns, no decorative elements.\n\n— Style references —\nFuturistic minimal art aesthetic. Visual touch-points: Bauhaus design (Kandinsky, Moholy-Nagy), De Stijl (Mondrian), Russian Suprematism (Malevich), contemporary 3D minimal artists like Filip Hodas, Pawel Nolbert, and Studio Brasch. Premium editorial poster discipline.\n\n— Composition framing —\nCaptured in {{aspect_ratio}} aspect ratio.\n\n— Additional details —\n{{extra_notes}}\n\n— Strictly avoid —\n- Do NOT use any color outside the {{color_1}} + {{color_2}} pairing (background color is the only exception)\n- Do NOT add gradients within a single shape — use solid flat color (or its softly-shaded 3D version of the same hue)\n- Do NOT add textures, patterns, noise, or grain to the shapes\n- Do NOT include any text, numbers, labels, watermarks, or logos\n- Do NOT crowd the frame — preserve generous negative space\n- Do NOT make shapes overlap chaotically — alignment must feel mathematically considered\n- Do NOT add hand-drawn or sketchy lines — every edge must be perfectly clean\n- Do NOT add lens flares, light rays, particles, or atmospheric effects\n- Do NOT make the original subject still literally recognizable as a photo — it must be fully abstracted into primitive geometry\n- Do NOT add decorative borders, frames, or vignettes\n- Do NOT use cliché tech UI elements (grids, HUD lines, technical drawings)\n\nKeywords: geometric breakdown, abstract minimalism, Bauhaus, duotone, primitive shapes, negative space, futuristic minimal, 3D minimal, editorial poster, clean composition",
